  "notes": [
    {
      "id": "81ba6f45-6887-ef11-8474-000d3a37e3b6",
      "type": "GeneralTitle",
      "area": "General",
      "position": 0,
      "content": "IMPORTANT MAJOR INFOMATION",
      "contentHtml": null
    },
    {
      "id": "80ba6f45-6887-ef11-8474-000d3a37e3b6",
      "type": "GeneralText",
      "area": "General",
      "position": 1,
      "content": "Linguistic Anthropology is an interdisciplinary field which addresses the manifold ways in which communication and culture mutually define one another in different communities worldwide. Courses are offered in ethnographic approaches to discourse analysis, urban sociolinguistics, field methods and conversational analysis, as well as cross cultural pragmatics, including visual aspects of communication. Listed below are the lower division preparation courses for this major. To be considered for this major, you must complete the following courses by the end of spring before transfer: One year of college level coursework in the declared language OR At least one year of high school in which the primary language of instruction was the declared language. Completion of introduction to linguistics and introduction to linguistic anthropology are STRONGLY RECOMMENDED . Completion of two years of college foreign language is STRONGLY RECOMMENDED . A placement exam for a language offered at UCLA may be taken upon transfer to test out of or make progress toward the major language requirement. All courses must be taken for a letter grade. For more information regarding this major and UCLA's transfer selection process, visit https://linguistics.ucla.edu and https:// admission.ucla.edu . PLEASE NOTE: the community college courses listed below have been approved to satisfy the preparation requirements for this major at UCLA, but they may not be exact equivalents of the UCLA courses listed.",
      "contentHtml": "<p>Linguistic Anthropology is an interdisciplinary field which addresses the manifold ways in which communication and culture mutually define one another in different communities worldwide. Courses are offered in ethnographic approaches to discourse analysis, urban sociolinguistics, field methods and conversational analysis, as well as cross cultural pragmatics, including visual aspects of communication.</p><p><br></p><p>Listed below are the lower division preparation courses for this major.</p><p><br></p><p>To be considered for this major, you must complete the following courses by the end of spring before transfer:</p><ul><li>One year of college level coursework in the declared language OR</li><li>At least one year of high school in which the primary language of instruction was the declared language.</li></ul><p>Completion of introduction to linguistics and introduction to linguistic anthropology are <strong>STRONGLY RECOMMENDED</strong>.</p><p>Completion of two years of college foreign language is <strong>STRONGLY RECOMMENDED</strong>. A placement exam for a language offered at UCLA may be taken upon transfer to test out of or make progress toward the major language requirement.</p><p>All courses must be taken for a letter grade.</p><p><br></p><p>For more information regarding this major and UCLA's transfer selection process, visit <u style=\"color: rgb(41, 98, 255);\">https://linguistics.ucla.edu</u> and <u style=\"color: rgb(41, 98, 255);\">https://</u><a href=\"http://www.admission.ucla.edu\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">admission.ucla.edu</a>.</p><p><br></p><p>PLEASE NOTE: the community college courses listed below have been approved to satisfy the preparation requirements for this major at UCLA, but they may not be exact equivalents of the UCLA courses listed.</p>"
    }
